{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475217"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12560"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12560"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.16,0.3,0.06,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5059"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38005"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1891"},{"type":"tags","id":"4919"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9404"},{"type":"tags","id":"11188"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15763"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA one-day-old boy is reviewed on the maternity ward with his parents. He was born at term via spontaneous vaginal delivery. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His parents express concern about the appearance of their child\u0027s face. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a distinct abnormality in the upper lip, characterised by a separation extending from the midline to the base of the nose on the left side. The defect appears to involve only the upper lip and does not extend to the palate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Maternal alcohol use","Maternal cytomegalovirus infection","Maternal folate deficiency","Maternal cocaine use","Maternal diabetes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario is born with a cleft lip. \u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal alcohol use\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly during the first trimester, has been associated with an increased risk of craniofacial malformations, including cleft lip. Alcohol interferes with normal embryonic development, disrupting cellular proliferation, migration, and differentiation. Maternal alcohol consumption should be avoided during pregnancy to prevent potential foetal harm. Maternal alcohol use can lead to foetal alcohol syndrome (FAS), which is a developmental and congenital disorder characterised by neurocognitive impairment, structural defects, and growth restriction due to prenatal alcohol exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal cytomegalovirus (CMV) infection\u003C/strong\u003E is a common viral infection that can be transmitted from mother to foetus during pregnancy. While CMV infection during pregnancy is a recognised cause of congenital abnormalities, including sensorineural hearing loss, microcephaly, and developmental delays, it is not a well-established cause of cleft lip. A cleft lip is typically associated with environmental and genetic factors rather than maternal infections such as CMV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal folate deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E during early pregnancy has been linked to neural tube defects, such as spina bifida, but the evidence supporting an association between folate deficiency and cleft lip is less conclusive. However, it is recommended that women of childbearing age consume adequate amounts of folic acid to reduce the risk of neural tube defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal cocaine use\u003C/strong\u003E during pregnancy has been associated with numerous adverse effects on foetal development. Cocaine can lead to vasoconstriction and impaired blood supply to the developing embryo, increasing the risk of various congenital abnormalities. However, there is limited evidence linking maternal cocaine use specifically to cleft lip formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly when poorly controlled, has been identified as a risk factor for the development of congenital anomalies, including cleft lip. The exact mechanisms underlying this association are not fully understood, but it is hypothesised that hyperglycaemia during critical periods of embryonic development may interfere with normal palatal fusion. Therefore, pregnant women with diabetes require close monitoring and strict glycaemic control to minimise the risk of foetal malformations. However, the incidence of cleft lip with maternal diabetes is low compared to maternal alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while all of these maternal factors can potentially impact foetal development, maternal alcohol use is the most strongly associated with the development of cleft lip. It\u0027s important to note that cleft lip can also occur without any identifiable cause, and a multidisciplinary approach involving paediatrics, plastic surgery, and genetics is often necessary for optimal management and to rule out associated syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Maternal alcohol consumption is a recognised risk factor for the development of cleft lip.","Cleft lip is a congenital defect characterised by a separation in the upper lip, often extending to the base of the nose.","Maternal alcohol use during pregnancy can lead to foetal alcohol syndrome, which includes craniofacial abnormalities."],"references":["Walker NJ, Anand S, Podda S. Cleft Lip. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2023 Jan 30. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482262/","Dyl\u0105g KA, Anunziata F, Bandoli G, Chambers C. Birth Defects Associated with Prenatal Alcohol Exposure-A Review. Children (Basel). 2023 Apr 29;10(5):811. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10217313/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38005"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12560"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38005"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-08T12:37:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-08T12:46:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5059"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52642"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":